---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;

const controls = [
  { c: 'b', t: 'Formation LP / IPM', d: 'A continuous linear program allocates the eleven players into an optimal team shape for the current phase — solved by Clarabel interior-point in optimized builds, with a deterministic simplex fallback for reproducibility.' },
  { c: 'b', t: 'Per-player MPC', d: 'Model-Predictive Control executes whatever the policy chose — dribble, pass or shot — projecting the intent forward against the body’s dynamics and a predicted opponent, and scoring its probability of success. When that probability is below a learned, context-dependent threshold it rejects the move and hands the decision back to the POMDP for its next-best action.' },
  { c: 'b', t: 'POMDP belief', d: 'No player observes the whole truth, so each maintains a belief over hidden variables — opponent press intent, anticipated pass trajectories — and decides in belief space.' },
  { c: 'g', t: 'Learned world model', d: 'A neural forward-dynamics model predicts the next state, giving the planner a receding-horizon view of where the ball and bodies are heading.' },
  { c: 'r', t: 'Anti-bunch & spacing discipline', d: 'Territorial-spacing nudges, defensive line push-up, and formation stagger keep 22 agents from collapsing onto the ball — each independently toggleable to A/B its effect.' },
  { c: 'b', t: 'Bounded PUCT search', d: 'An optional shallow lookahead re-ranks the policy’s top candidates using the value head and world model — search over a learned prior, kept cheap enough for real-time.' },
];
---
<Base title="The Engine — Akrion Soccer Engine" description="How the Akrion Soccer Engine applies intelligent control to 22-player football: discrete-event simulation, formation LP/IPM, POMDP belief, and per-player MPC.">
  <section class="section head">
    <div class="wrap">
      <p class="eyebrow">The Engine</p>
      <h1>Intelligent control for 22&#8209;player football</h1>
      <p class="lede">
        A match is a discrete-event system: a continuous world sampled tick by tick,
        where 22 agents each decide and act under partial information. The Akrion engine
        resolves that with layered optimal control — allocation, belief, prediction and
        model-predictive execution — all on a general Rust simulation core.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <hr class="hr" />

  <!-- DES -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="wrap">
      <div class="split">
        <div class="reveal">
          <p class="eyebrow">Discrete-event foundation</p>
          <h2>A match, modeled as events in time</h2>
          <p>
            Underneath the soccer domain sits <code>des_engine</code> — the
            <a href="https://github.com/akrion-sim" target="_blank" rel="noopener">discrete-event-system.rs</a>
            core. It is a general Rust SDK for modeling, simulating, solving and rendering
            discrete, continuous and mixed systems through one uniform, JSON-first API.
          </p>
          <p>
            The soccer engine is transport-agnostic by design: construct a
            <code>SoccerMatch</code> or <code>SoccerRealtimeSession</code> and drive it
            directly — no HTTP required. Web servers merely wrap it. Every run produces a
            machine-readable artifact of frames, results and summary.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="codeblock reveal">
          <div class="code-top"><span class="d r"></span><span class="d g"></span><span class="d b"></span><em>simulation pipeline</em></div>
          <pre><code>JSON spec / command stream
        │
        ▼
  des_engine runner / solver
        │
        ▼
  RunArtifact &#123; frames, results, summary &#125;
        │
        ├─▶ report.html   interactive player
        ├─▶ results.json  machine-readable
        └─▶ frames.jsonl  one frame / line</code></pre>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <hr class="hr" />

  <!-- CONTROL LAYERS -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="wrap">
      <div class="reveal" style="max-width:720px; margin-bottom:44px;">
        <p class="eyebrow">Control layers</p>
        <h2>How 22 agents are guided every tick</h2>
        <p class="lede">
          Intelligent control here means several optimizers cooperating: a global one for
          team shape, a local one per player for execution, and learned models feeding
          both. Any discipline can be switched off to measure its contribution.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="grid grid-3">
        {controls.map((x) => (
          <article class={`card accent-${x.c} reveal`}>
            <span class="topbar"></span>
            <h3>{x.t}</h3>
            <p>{x.d}</p>
          </article>
        ))}
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <hr class="hr" />

  <!-- WHY IT MATTERS -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="wrap">
      <div class="split">
        <div class="codeblock reveal">
          <div class="code-top"><span class="d r"></span><span class="d g"></span><span class="d b"></span><em>allocation vs. execution</em></div>
          <pre><code>team shape        →  Formation LP / IPM
                     (global, 11 slots)

per-player intent →  Policy head (actor)
                     GK · DEF · MID · FWD

execution         →  MPC trajectory
                     scores P(success) per intent
                     reject → POMDP next-best

result            →  pass · shoot · dribble
                     move · tackle</code></pre>
        </div>
        <div class="reveal">
          <p class="eyebrow">Global × local</p>
          <h2>Two optimizers, one coherent team</h2>
          <p>
            A linear program decides the <strong>team’s</strong> optimal shape — where the
            eleven slots should be. Model-Predictive Control decides each
            <strong>player’s</strong> optimal path to fill their slot without violating the
            physics of a body in motion. Between them sits the learned policy, choosing
            what to actually do with the ball.
          </p>
          <p>
            This separation is what makes the system both principled and fast: exact
            optimization where the problem is convex, learned judgment where it isn’t, and
            MPC to keep every action physically honest.
          </p>
          <div class="cta"><a class="btn btn-primary" href={`${base}learning`}>How the policy is learned →</a></div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</Base>

<style>
  .head h1 { max-width: 16ch; }
  .head .lede { margin-top: 18px; }
  .split { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 44px; align-items: center; }
  @media (max-width: 880px) { .split { grid-template-columns: 1fr; gap: 28px; } }
  .split p { color: var(--ink-soft); }
  .cta { margin-top: 24px; }

  .codeblock { border: 1px solid var(--line); border-radius: var(--radius); overflow: hidden; background: var(--bg-2); box-shadow: 0 24px 60px -40px #000; }
  .code-top { display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 7px; padding: 12px 16px; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--line); background: rgba(255,255,255,0.02); }
  .code-top .d { width: 10px; height: 10px; border-radius: 50%; display: inline-block; }
  .code-top .d.r { background: var(--red-bright); }
  .code-top .d.g { background: var(--green-bright); }
  .code-top .d.b { background: var(--blue-bright); }
  .code-top em { margin-left: auto; font-style: normal; font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: 0.72rem; color: var(--ink-dim); }
  .codeblock pre { margin: 0; padding: 22px; overflow-x: auto; }
  .codeblock code { font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: 0.84rem; color: var(--ink-soft); line-height: 1.7; white-space: pre; }
</style>
